@mibcat: The auto world does not like FOSS too much :-( 

But you could actually use the source code to create your own fork of BUSMASTER, which would run on Linux...

Or: maybe you get it running with WINE ?

I successfully sent a message with a changing signal using Node Simulation. You can send ANY Signal your piece of C++ code can realize.
E.g:
 
//warning, untested code, please do a dry run on the console.
//in the 10ms Timer Handler:
//don't forget to include stdint.h and math.h in "include headers"
//also note that you will have to properly shift/format your signal according to your specific
//message layout. Easy to do if you "speak" C++.
    static time = 0;
    short y = (int16_t) (sin(time * 2 * 3.1415f / 360.0f) * 100);
     STCAN_MSG msg;
     msg.id = 0x18EF70C9;
     msg.isExtended = true;
     msg.isRtr = false;
     msg.dlc = 8;
     msg.data[0] = 0;
     msg.data[1] = 0;
     msg.data[2] = 0;
     msg.data[3] = 0;
     msg.data[4] = y ;
     msg.data[5] = y >> 8;
     msg.data[6] = 0;
     msg.data[7] = 0;
     msg.cluster = 1;
     time++;
     SendMsg(msg);

