I have been tracking this issue with Busmaster for some time now, across multiple versions.  I am currently testing with version 3.2.2.   I create a node simulation with a message handler for some CAN Id, lets say Message01 with an ID of 0x100.  In that handler I copy the value of a signal into the signal of another message and send it as shown below.  In this example, both signals are 16 bit unsigned with a scale factor of 0.25:

```
void OnMsgName_Message01(Message01 RxMsg)
{
        Message02_tx.Signal01.rawvalue(RxMsg.Signal01);
	SendMsg(PUMA_EngSpd_tx);
}
```
Initial, the signal graph will show the 2 signals perfectly superimposed on eachother, as they should be.  Over time, Message02 will delay more and more, eventually being anywhere from 2-10 seconds behind Message01.  The amount of time it takes to reach this level of delay various among different computers, but it happens on all of them.  The delay between the 2 signals can start appearing as fast as 30 minuts on some machines, to as long as 4 hours on others. Also, as the delay gets worse, the memory usage for Busmaster in the task manager climbs from the typical 50-55 MB to over 100MB to even 250MB, and the UI becomes very sluggish until Busmaster is closed and re-opened.  It usually takes at least 6-8 hours on all machines for the memory usage to climb and the UI to become sluggish and unresponsive.   Also, once the delay has started and memory usage has started to increase, Busmaster will crash with an unhandled exception when disconnected.  It does not crash upon disconnect when there is no delay between the 2 signals.

I have tested this for 24 hour durations on other CAN hardware including Vector PCI, Vector USB, and ETAS ES593 and this issue does not exist.  The 2 signals stay superimposed perfectly, and memory usage never changes.

