Regards
Mads Nygaard

Yes, it works nicely for me.

Just create a Node and add the following Timer code. It will create a Huuuge ramp from 0 to 65535. Then again 0...

     static int i=0;  
     STCAN_MSG msg;
     msg.id = 0x18EF70C9;
     msg.isExtended = true;
     msg.isRtr = false;
     msg.dlc = 8;
     msg.data[0] = 0;
     msg.data[1] = 0;
     msg.data[2] = 0;
     msg.data[3] = 0;
     msg.data[4] = i ;
     msg.data[5] = i >> 8;
     msg.data[6] = 0;
     msg.data[7] = 0;
     msg.cluster = 1;
     i++;
     SendMsg(msg);

You can create and run as many node simulations as you want, but no method exists in Busmaster to pass data in between simulated nodes.  In Vector products (CANoe/CANalyzer) this is done via environment variables or system variables.  

See my issue https://github.com/rbei-etas/busmaster/issues/839 . I needed to share data between a CAN node and a LIN node.  Since MinGW is used to compile node simulations, you have the entire Windows API at your disposal.  I ended up creating a shared memory segment as shown in the last comment, which makes ' lpvMem' a pointer to memory available to all nodes that use that code.  You also have to put the following lines in the global variable section of each node simulation:
```
static LPVOID lpvMem = NULL;
static HANDLE hMapObject = NULL;
BOOL fInit, fIgnore;
```

