I created a small test simulation & database to describe this problem. I created a dbf with 6 Motorola unsigned ints in msg01.  The first 3 in order are 8 bit, then 2 16 bit, then one more 8 bit.  The problem is that busmaster simulated node refuses to send a 16bit signal at byte index 4 (which would be 3 and 4), instead it transmit the signal data on byte 4 and byte 5, so it overwrites half of the following signal.  The next 16 bit signal is also shifted over by 1 byte, and finally, the last signal in the message doesnt show up in the message at all.  In the simulation, Sig04 in msg01 has a padding byte added to the struct which shouldn't be there.  Even if I comment it out though, the signal is still packed into the message incorrectly.  It will pack correctly if move Sig04 up to the first, second, or third location, but it always jumps over byte location 4.  In the simulation I send:

Msg01_tx.m_sWhichBit.Sig04 = 0x1234;

and the result is: 
00 00 00 00 34 12 00 00

It should be:
00 00 00 34 12 00 00 00

I am aware of the byte order issue #750 but this is something else.

I created msg02 full of 8 bytes, no problems there.  I can send a zip file of the small (25KB) simulation if anyone wants it.

